5-07-2026

Today I was working on implementing binary search.

At first I used unsigned int for left and right, but I ran into a problem. If I accidentally do something like:

0 - 1

an unsigned integer can't store negative values, so it underflows and becomes a very large positive number (for example, 4294967295 on a 32-bit unsigned integer).

Then I tried size_t, thinking it would solve the problem.

It didn't.

size_t has the exact same issue because it's also an unsigned integer type. It can't represent negative numbers, so subtracting below zero causes underflow.

For now, I'm considering using int instead because it supports negative values, making the logic easier while I'm learning.

I also learned that many C++ implementations still use size_t for indexing containers because indices are never supposed to be negative. When using size_t, you have to structure the binary search carefully to avoid underflow, especially when updating right = mid - 1 if mid is 0.

This was a good reminder that choosing a type isn't just about its size—it's about the range of values it can safely represent.


